<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_app-ring" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Application: Moment of Inertia for a Ring</title>
		

<activity xml:id="class_mars-moons">
        <title>Warm-up: The Moons of Mars</title>
		<statement>
		<p></p>
		    <p>
				Mars has two moons, Phobos and Deimos, which have the following orbital properties:
				<me>R_p = 9 \times 10^6 \mathrm{~m}</me>
				<me>R_d = 20 \times 10^6 \mathrm{~m}</me>
				<me>M_p = 11 \times 10^15 \mathrm{~kg}</me>
				<me>M_d = 2 \times 10^15 \mathrm{~kg}</me>
			</p>
			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						Sketch a diagram showing Mars, Phobos, and Deimos.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
Find the moment of inertia of each moon (on it's own) about an axis passing through Mars
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
Find the moment of inertia for the system consisting of the two moons about an axis passing through Mars
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>
		</statement>
	</activity>

	<activity xml:id="class_ring-i">
	<title>The Ring</title>
<introduction>
<p></p>
    <p>
      The ring shown below has mass <m>m</m>, inner radius <m>r_i</m>, and outer radius <m>r_o</m>. Calculate the moment of inertia about an axis through the center, perpendicular to the screen.
    </p>
	<figure xml:id="fig_rot-ring-i">
			<title>Ring Figure</title>
			<caption>A ball suspended from the ceiling by a string.</caption>
			<image source="ring-i.png" width = "50%">
				<description></description>
			</image>
		</figure>
	</introduction>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Explain why the mass density can be given by: <me>
					\sigma = \frac{m}{\pi(r_o^2 - r_i^2)}
				</me>
				
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				<alert>Chop:</alert> How would you chop the ring up into small pieces? Draw a diagram showing the small pieces and label <m>dm</m>, <m>dA</m>, and <m>r</m>.  Find the mass of one of the small pieces you drew.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				<alert>Multiply:</alert> Using the results from the previous steps, multiply the components together to get your infinitesimal <m>dl</m>.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				<alert>Add:</alert> Compute the integral for the moment of inertia.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Use special-case analysis in the limit that <m>r_i</m> approaches <m>r_o</m> to make sense of your answer.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Use the parallel axis theorem to find the moment of inertia of the ring about an axis passing through its outer edge (perpendicular to the ring).
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
	<task>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Use an integral to verify the center of mass of the ring.
			</p>
		</statement>
	</task>
</activity>



	
</section>

